{
  "slug": "is-2019-the-worst-movie-summer-ever-men-in-black-internation",
  "title": "Is 2019 the Worst Movie Summer Ever? 'Men in Black: International' Isn't Helping",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2019-06-18",
  "runtimeMin": 69,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda both took solo trips to 'Men in Black: International,' then use its flop to argue about whether 2019 is really the worst summer at the movies ever, or just another year with a few good ones and a pile of bad ones.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "'Men in Black: International'",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Men in Black: International",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "A re-origin with no Will Smith, no Tommy Lee Jones, no Barry Sonnenfeld: F. Gary Gray directs Chris Hemsworth, Tessa Thompson, Liam Neeson and Emma Thompson. It's not offensive or a disaster, just a mess. The CGI (Kumail Nanjiani's six-inch alien) replaces the tactile Rick Baker creature charm, and Hemsworth is miscast as the institution man when his gift is playing the wisecracking outsider. Made $30 million on opening weekend, a bomb."
        },
        {
          "title": "Men in Black",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "The Will Smith / Tommy Lee Jones original the hosts keep measuring this against. Everyone plays the aliens straight except Smith, the audience's Fresh Prince proxy, and it ends on a song. Amanda remembers Vincent D'Onofrio's bug and not much else."
        },
        {
          "title": "Guardians of the Galaxy",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "How much does it owe the original Men in Black, or does the first Men in Black owe the Guardians comics? Same fun, goofy, family-friendly alien tone."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Amazing Spider-Man",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "The reboot analogy: this is the Andrew Garfield to Tobey Maguire's, a redundant restart barely a decade after the last one."
        },
        {
          "title": "Independence Day",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "The mega-blockbuster register the first Men in Black was a tonal break from."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The movie-star problem",
      "note": "Hemsworth, Tessa Thompson, and whether you can open a movie without a comic book",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Bad Times at the El Royale",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Hemsworth's stylish noir swing. Bombed; maybe better than it looked at the time."
        },
        {
          "title": "12 Strong",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "The horse-soldiers war movie. Bombed."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ghostbusters",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Fraught release, but both hosts agree Hemsworth is fantastic in it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Huntsman: Winter's War",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "They handed him the franchise off 'Snow White and the Huntsman.' Bombed."
        },
        {
          "title": "In the Heart of the Sea",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "The seafaring historical epic. Bombed."
        },
        {
          "title": "Vacation",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "Fine."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blackhat",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "His Michael Mann crime movie. 'World-historical mismanaged bomb.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rush",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "The racing drama. Bombed."
        },
        {
          "title": "Red Dawn",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "Bombed. The rundown proving Hemsworth has never worked outside of Thor."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dear White People",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "Part of Tessa Thompson's indie run."
        },
        {
          "title": "Selma",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "Thompson's steady body of work before the franchises."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sorry to Bother You",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Another Thompson indie the hosts rate."
        },
        {
          "title": "Creed",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "The role that made her well-known."
        },
        {
          "title": "Annihilation",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "A bomb, and she wasn't even really the lead, though it's her biggest non-Marvel movie besides Creed."
        },
        {
          "title": "Star Trek",
          "year": 2009,
          "note": "Chris Pine's 'comic book of its own kind,' the exception that mostly proves nobody strings together non-comic-book hits."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hell or High Water",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Pine's smaller-movie, indie-route success."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wonder Woman",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "Pine delightful as the supporting man."
        },
        {
          "title": "J. Edgar",
          "year": 2011,
          "note": "Leonardo DiCaprio's occasional miss. He's otherwise the last star who reliably opens a non-franchise movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bird Box",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Sandra Bullock as the closest thing to Leo, though the hosts argue Netflix and the memes made it a phenomenon as much as she did."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The weekend at the box office",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Shaft (2019)",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Tim Story's reboot bombed even harder than Men in Black: about $7 million. Two Black filmmakers had the two biggest wide releases of the weekend, both flops."
        },
        {
          "title": "Shaft (2000)",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "The John Singleton one grossed $117 million; this new one made a fraction of it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Murder Mystery",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The Adam Sandler / Jennifer Aniston Netflix comedy, an Agatha Christie cruise-ship setup caught between parody and the real thing. Amanda, a devoted Christie reader, was extremely disappointed; Sean thought it was fine. Written by James Vanderbilt."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rolling Thunder Revue: A Bob Dylan Story by Martin Scorsese",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Scorsese's Bob Dylan documentary on Netflix, the movie every man in Amanda's life told her about. Sean's dad's review: 'interesting.' Sean's: 'it kicks ass.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Souvenir",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Sean's dad saw it and 'Rolling Thunder Revue' the same weekend, a blessed Father's Day."
        },
        {
          "title": "Late Night",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Did worse than 'Booksmart'; will play better on Amazon Prime, which paid $13 million for it at Sundance."
        },
        {
          "title": "Booksmart",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Around $20 million, actually not bad, though it was hyped as the 'Superbad' phenomenon that never quite arrived. Should have opened in August."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Secret Life of Pets 2",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Precipitous sequel drop. Amanda would happily watch it as three-minute phone clips."
        },
        {
          "title": "Toy Story 4",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Out Friday. Sean calls it absolutely brilliant, and the movie that cooks 'Secret Life of Pets 2.' Amanda will not watch it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Last Black Man in San Francisco",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "As old-school an A24 hit as there can be: great word of mouth, slow platform rollout from four theaters up."
        },
        {
          "title": "Clue",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "The board-game movie that actually pulls off mocking the mystery genre while being one, the bar 'Murder Mystery' fails to clear."
        },
        {
          "title": "Zodiac",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "Also written by James Vanderbilt, which is why 'Murder Mystery' theoretically should have been smarter."
        },
        {
          "title": "Toni Morrison: The Pieces I Am",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "A head-on documentary about the novelist. Not a 'wow' movie, but 'an excellent iTunes rental,' where a lot of good films are headed."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The state of the summer movie",
      "note": "what makes a good summer, what's still coming, and a decade of good-and-bad rundowns",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Yesterday",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The high-concept, low-execution movie-for-everybody the hosts hope will fill the out-of-nowhere slot. Sean's had the premise conversation with strangers at parties."
        },
        {
          "title": "Midsommar",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Ari Aster's 'Hereditary' follow-up. Sean's excited; Amanda won't be going."
        },
        {
          "title": "Spider-Man: Far From Home",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The one they trust to be good 'in the container in which it comes': John Watts back, Gyllenhaal as Mysterio, a fancy Italian school trip."
        },
        {
          "title": "Once Upon a Time in Hollywood",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The summer's plausible sneaky Oscar contender."
        },
        {
          "title": "Fast & Furious Presents: Hobbs & Shaw",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Coming August 2, strange and, by the same token, clever timing."
        },
        {
          "title": "John Wick: Chapter 3 - Parabellum",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The best actual summer movie so far: bigger than the last one, does exactly what its fans want."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rocketman",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Floated as a retrofitted-Oscar broad-appeal contender; nobody's sure it counts."
        },
        {
          "title": "Die Hard with a Vengeance",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "The 1995 slate's proof that a third installment can rule. It was built from a non-'Die Hard' script called 'Simon Says,' and it put Samuel L. Jackson to work right after 'Pulp Fiction.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Toy Story 3",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "The 2010 'good' column: Oscar-nominated then, quietly reappraised as lesser now in the wake of 4."
        },
        {
          "title": "Inception",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "Big summer hit; Sean thinks it's very flawed, which once made everyone mad at 'The Rewatchables.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Scott Pilgrim vs. the World",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "Edgar Wright, way ahead of its time and mis-marketed into a non-hit. 'Fuck yeah.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "The American",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "George Clooney's slow, beautifully shot assassin drama: little seen, a Sam Donski classic."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Fault in Our Stars",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "When YA still mattered at the movies: the rare one without a fantasy hook, and the one everybody wept through."
        },
        {
          "title": "Edge of Tomorrow",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "Took on cult status after the fact."
        },
        {
          "title": "22 Jump Street",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "An actually good sequel."
        },
        {
          "title": "Boyhood",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "The great film in the 2014 good column."
        },
        {
          "title": "Chef",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "Jon Favreau making the movies we think JJ Abrams is trying to make. Sean's uncomplicated favorite, filed last."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mad Max: Fury Road",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "The sneaky-Oscar-contender ideal: basically does everything a great summer movie should."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dunkirk",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "One of the recent sneaky Oscar contenders a good summer needs."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
